TL;DR¶

In this exercise i will try to solve the Kaggle contest "House Prices - Advanced Regression Techniques"

i will need to predict house prices in Ames, Iowa, according to vast variety of 80 features.

In order to do that i will need to analyze the data so i could find a connections between house features and its predicted price.

i will pick the best features for my modle and i will perform cross validation and i will perform ML regression on the data.

def count_empty_values_in_each_column(d: pd.DataFrame):
    print('empty values')
    print('------------\n')

    empty_columns = []
    for col in d.columns:
        empty = d[col].isna().sum()
        if empty != 0:
            empty_columns.append(col)
            print(f"{col}: {empty}")
    return empty_columns

def fill_na_median(x, column_names):
    for column_name in column_names:
        x[column_name].fillna(x[column_name].median(),inplace = True)

def fill_na_mean(x, column_names):
    for column_name in column_names:
        x[column_name].fillna(x[column_name].mean(),inplace = True)

def fill_na_mode(df, column_names):
    for column_name in column_names:
        df[column_name].fillna(df[column_name].mode()[0], inplace=True) 

def getObjects(data):
    return data.select_dtypes('object').columns

def outliers_iqr(ys):# gets numric column and return indexs in array
    quartile_1, quartile_3 = np.percentile(ys, [25, 75]) #Get 1st and 3rd quartiles (25% -> 75% of data will be kept)
    iqr = quartile_3 - quartile_1
    lower_bound = quartile_1 - (iqr * 1.5) #Get lower bound
    upper_bound = quartile_3 + (iqr * 1.5) #Get upper bound
    return np.where((ys > upper_bound) | (ys < lower_bound)) #Get outlier values

def DropOutliers(data):# need to do : x = thefunction
    for column in data:
        outlierValuesList = np.ndarray.tolist(outliers_iqr(data[column])[0]) #outliers_iqr() returns an array
    return data.drop(outlierValuesList) #Drop outlier rows

def getOutliers(data):# need to do : x = thefunction
    for column in data:
        outlierValuesList = np.ndarray.tolist(outliers_iqr(data[column])[0]) #outliers_iqr() returns an array
    return outlierValuesList

Functions for finding what to drop¶

  • Dealing with NULL values
  • Distinct catagories fall into same catagories.
  • features that are correlated to each other
  • not Correlated With the target
In [6]:
#Dealing with NULL values
def dropColumnsMoreThen_Nan(data):
    data.dropna(axis=1, how='any', thresh = 1000,inplace = True) #Drop columns that contain more than 40% NULL values

# dropping Distinct catagories fall into same catagories.
def dropDistinctOnThreshold(data, valThreshold):
    number_of_rows = len(data)
    drop_list = []
    for col in data.columns:
        highest_freq_val = data[col].mode()[0]
        appearance_num = (data[col] == highest_freq_val).sum()
        if (appearance_num / number_of_rows) > valThreshold:
            drop_list.append(col)
    return drop_list


#Drop features that are correlated to each other
def FeaturesCorrelatedToEachOther(data):
    covarianceMatrix = data.corr()
    listOfFeatures = [i for i in covarianceMatrix]
    setOfDroppedFeatures = set() 
    for i in range(len(listOfFeatures)) :
        for j in range(i+1,len(listOfFeatures)): #Avoid repetitions 
            feature1=listOfFeatures[i]
            feature2=listOfFeatures[j]
            if abs(covarianceMatrix[feature1][feature2]) > 0.8: #If the correlation between the features is > 0.8
                setOfDroppedFeatures.add(feature1) #Add one of them to the set
                                                   #I tried different values of threshold and 0.8 was the one that gave the best results
    return setOfDroppedFeatures

def nonCorrelatedWithOutput(data):
    nonCorrelatedWithOutput = [column for column in data if abs(data[column].corr(data["SalePrice"])) < 0.045]
    #I tried different values of threshold and 0.045 was the one that gave the best results
    return nonCorrelatedWithOutput

def show_accuracy_by_encoder(dfs, encoder_names):
    accuracy_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['encoder_name', 'split', 'accuracy'])

    for i, df in enumerate(dfs):
        X = df.drop(['SalePrice'],axis=1)
        t = df['SalePrice']
        X_train, X_val, t_train, t_val = train_test_split(X, t, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
        encoder_name = encoder_names[i]
        model = LinearRegression()
        model.fit(X_train, t_train)
        accuracy_df.loc[len(accuracy_df)] = [encoder_name, 'train', model.score(X_train, t_train)]
        accuracy_df.loc[len(accuracy_df)] = [encoder_name, 'val', model.score(X_val, t_val)]

    fig = px.bar(accuracy_df, x='encoder_name', y='accuracy', color='split', barmode='group')
    #img_bytes = fig.to_image(format="png", width=600, height=350, scale=2)
    display(fig)
    
def encode(df, columns_names, enc):
    df_cp = df.copy()
    feature_names = [str(name) for name in data_object]
    if enc == le:
        df_enc = df_cp.copy()
        for features in feature_names:
            df_enc[features] = le.fit_transform(df_cp[features].astype(str))
    else:
        df_cat = df_cp[columns_names]
        df_cat_enc = pd.DataFrame(enc.fit_transform(df_cat))
        df_enc = df_cp.drop(columns_names, axis=1).join(df_cat_enc)
    return df_enc

conclusion from the correlations¶

Correlation is a statistical measure that describes the association between random variables. It is one of the most widely used statistical concepts. In our case, we can view correlation from two different points of view:

  1. Correlation of features with each other

  2. Correlation of features with output

  • In the first case, we will tend to drop features that are correlated to each other, since a high correlation between features indicates that the features bring up almost the same information, so it will be a waste of time and a waste of resources to consider such features.

conclusion : i will drop features that are correlated to each other more then 80%

  • In the second case, we will tend to drop features that are not correlated to the output, since a low correlation between a feature and the output indicates that such feature is not really associatied with output and doesn't contribute much to the final result.

conclusion : i will drop correlation threshold - 0.045 with 'SalePrice'

Feature Selection¶

Now i will :

1.make a big function for visultion

2. use backwords feature selection in order to decide which features are best to use in our model.

3. i will try two model LinearRegression and SGDRegressor and check who gives me the best result

note:¶

backwords feature selection start from a full set of features and drop features until it reaches the best score.

i choose it becuse :

  • It is simple and easy to implement.

  • It is relatively fast, since it involves training a model with all the features before pruning them one by one.

  • It can help to improve the interpretability of the model by reducing the number of features and making the model simpler.

  • It can help to improve the performance of the model by eliminating features that are not useful or contribute noise to the model.

However, it's important to note that backward feature selection is not always the best approach, and it may not work well in all situations. It may be more computationally expensive than other feature selection methods, and it may not always find the optimal set of features for a given problem.

# Required methods:
def find_generator_len(generator, useProgressBar = True):
    i = 0
    
    if useProgressBar:
        pbar = tqdm(desc = "Calculating Length", ncols = 1000, bar_format = "{desc}{bar:10}{r_bar}")
    for a in generator:
        i += 1
        if useProgressBar:
            pbar.update()

    if useProgressBar:
        pbar.close()

    return i

def get_cv_score_and_loss(x, t, model, k = None, p = None, showGraphs = False, showProgressBar = True):
    resultsDF = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Fold ID", "Split", "Score", "Loss"])
    cvMethod = ""

    if k is not None:
        cvMethod = "K-Fold"
        cv = KFold(n_splits = k, shuffle = True, random_state = 42)
    elif p is not None:
        cvMethod = f"Leave-{p}-Out"
        cv = LeavePOut(p)
    else:
        raise ValueError("Choose k (for K-Fold) or p (for Leave-P-Out)")

    if showProgressBar:
        pbar = tqdm(desc = "Computing Models", total = find_generator_len(cv.split(x)))

    for i, (trainIDs, validationIDs) in enumerate(cv.split(x)):
        xTrain = x.iloc[trainIDs]
        tTrain = t.iloc[trainIDs]
        xValidation = x.iloc[validationIDs]
        tValidation = t.iloc[validationIDs]
        model.fit(xTrain, tTrain)
        yTrain = model.predict(xTrain)
        yValidation = model.predict(xValidation)
        resultsDF.loc[len(resultsDF)] = [i, "train", model.score(xTrain, tTrain),mean_squared_error(tTrain, yTrain, squared=False)]
        resultsDF.loc[len(resultsDF)] = [i, "validation", model.score(xValidation, tValidation),mean_squared_error(tValidation, yValidation, squared=False)]
    
        if showProgressBar:
            pbar.update()
    if showProgressBar:
        pbar.close()

    val_resultsDF = resultsDF[resultsDF["Split"] == "validation"]
    train_resultsDF = resultsDF[resultsDF["Split"] == "train"]

    validationScoreMean = val_resultsDF["Score"].mean()
    validationLossMean = val_resultsDF["Loss"].mean()
    trainScoreMean = train_resultsDF["Score"].mean()
    trainLossMean = train_resultsDF["Loss"].mean()

    if showGraphs:
        scoreTitle = f"{k if k is not None else p} {cvMethod} (Score):<br />Mean Validation Score: {validationScoreMean:.2f}<br />Mean Train Score: {trainScoreMean:.2f}"
        lossTitle = f"{k if k is not None else p} {cvMethod} (Loss):<br />Mean Validation Loss: {validationLossMean:.2f}<br />Mean Train Loss: {trainLossMean:.2f}"

        scoreFig = px.line(resultsDF, x = "Fold ID", y = "Score", color = "Split", title = scoreTitle)
        scoreFig.show()

        lossFig = px.line(resultsDF, x = "Fold ID", y = "Loss", color = "Split", title = lossTitle)
        lossFig.show()

Hyper-Parameters Search¶

Regularization Techniques¶

Let's implement regularization by finding out the best combination of penalty and alpha, out of the next possible options:

1. Penlaty (Regularization methods): l1 (Ridge), l2 (Lasso), elasticnet

2. Alpha (Regularization constant): 0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1

3. Eta0 (Learning rate constant): 0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1

i will do that by using GridSearch.

i checked on the internet and i didnt find any params to play with that can affect the results ..

the params i found is : {'normalize': [True, False],'fit_intercept': [True, False],'copy_X': [True, False]}

note :¶

Alternatively, if learning_rate is set to a value other than "constant",

the eta0 hyperparameter may be used differently during training.

For example, if learning_rate is set to "invscaling",

the eta0 hyperparameter is used to define an inverse scaling factor that is applied to the step size at each iteration.

This can help to reduce the step size over time and fine-tune the model parameters as training progresses.

# train with grid search and get best parameters
def getOptimalHyperParameters(x, t):
    TheReg = SGDRegressor(random_state = 42)
    print(f'For {str(TheReg)} :\n')
    hyperParams = {"penalty": ["l2", "l1", "elasticnet"], "alpha": [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1], "eta0": [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1]}
    gridSearch = GridSearchCV(TheReg, param_grid = hyperParams).fit(x, t)
    print("Best hyper-parameters:")
    x3,x2,x1 = gridSearch.best_params_["penalty"], gridSearch.best_params_["eta0"],gridSearch.best_params_["alpha"]
    print(f"\teta0: {x2}\n\talpha: {x1}\n\tpenalty: {x3}\n\t")
    return x3,x2,x1

def readTest1():
    Harta = pd.read_csv("/kaggle/input/task2-dorirose/test.csv")
    Harta.drop(columns = 'Id', axis = 1,inplace = True)
    Harta.replace('', np.NaN, inplace=True)
    return Harta

def getfixedTestData(final_test):
    dropColumnsMoreThen_Nan(final_test)
    tdata_object = final_test.select_dtypes('object').columns
    tdata_numeric = final_test.select_dtypes(['float64','int64']).columns
    all_cols = tdata_object.tolist() + tdata_numeric.tolist()
    fill_na_mean(final_test,tdata_numeric.tolist())
    fill_na_mode(final_test,tdata_object.tolist())
    final_test = pd.get_dummies(final_test, columns=data_object.tolist(), prefix=data_object.tolist(),drop_first = True)
    scaler2 = MinMaxScaler()
    bnotDummey = final_test.select_dtypes(['float64','int64']).columns
    ct = make_column_transformer((scaler2,bnotDummey),remainder = 'passthrough')
    transformed_features = final_test.columns
    temp = ct.fit_transform(final_test)
    Xz = pd.DataFrame(temp,columns=transformed_features)
    return Xz

# Creating a submission file for the competition
def createCSVfile(model,x,theName):
    predicts = model.predict(x)
    submission = pd.read_csv("/kaggle/input/task2-dorirose/sample_submission.csv")
    submission["SalePrice"] = np.exp(predicts.astype(float))
    strx = "submission"+theName+".csv"
    submission.to_csv(strx,index=False)
    print(f'{strx} created !')

Contest Summary¶

In this contest, I attempted to predict the prices of houses in Ames, Iowa. First, I got a visual display about the data in order to obtain details about missing values, correlations,Non correlations and outliers. After filling missing values and dropping expendable ones, I headed for the linear regression and SGD regressor.

In the both, I have used backwords feature selection to find the best features for this module, activated Regularization and i have tested Cross Validation using K-Fold.

note : i used the gridSearch for getting the best params for SGD regressor. i wanted to find which Regularization kind considering also with the alpha and eta0.

I ended up using the - eta0: 0.1 alpha: 0.01 penalty: elasticnet
